column4: Work Experience of the Family categories are constructed by summing the number of hours worked in the prior 12 months by persons 18 and older for each family. Families with over 3,500 hours of work are labeled as having the equivalent of “Two Full-Time, Year-Round Workers.”  Families with 2,341 through 3,499 hours are labeled “One Full-Time, Year-Round and One Part-Time Worker.” Families with at least 1,750 through 2,340 hours are identified as “One Full-Time, Year-Round Worker.” Families with at least one hour of work, but less than 1,750 hours, are called “Less than One Full-Time, Year-Round Worker.” Finally, there are families that have “No Work.”

column2: the dollar difference between NYCgov family income and the NYCgov threshold
column3: Dollar amount
column4:
Since it is determined at the family level, all family members have the same poverty gap as their family head. Users should exercise caution to avoid inappropriate duplicative counting.  The poverty gap estimates – in particular, total and average amount of resources needed to  move people out of poverty – should be calculated at the family level if the purpose is to provide a guide for resource allocation .  

To estimate family-level poverty gap amounts (i.e., NYCgov_PovGap):

• retain only the reference person of each family in poverty (Povunit_Rel==1 & NYCgov_Poverty == 1)

• run relevant estimator (i.e., means or totals) over desired population subgroup. 
Use caution when interpreting the poverty gap amount across population subgroups or over time.  Apparent differences in average poverty gap may, to some extent, be a reflection of changes in threshold over time, a difference in family size or a function of individuals within a population rising out of poverty. See Chapter 3  of NYCgov Poverty Measure Report, 2005-2016 (published 2018) for more on the poverty gap.

column2: the poverty gap expressed as a proportion of the poverty threshold
column3: Ratio of family resources to their threshold
column4: The poverty gap is a dollar measure of resources needed to escape poverty. The poverty gap index captures the intensity of poverty - the difference in economic well-being as individuals get closer to (or surpass) their poverty threshold. It is possible for populations with similar poverty rates to have divergent poverty gap indexes. We recommend that estimates of the poverty gap index should be calculated for individuals, not family, to capture the full number of people affected. See Chapter 3  of NYCgov Poverty Measure Report, 2005-2016 (published 2018) for more on the poverty gap and its use.
